st" xss=removed><b xss=removed><span xss=removed><span xss=removed>4)<span xss=removed>      </span></span></span></b><b xss=removed>In learning hours: </b>for basic pathology\r\nand microbiology at least 10 hours should be allowed.</p><p>\r\n\r\n<br></p>', '2018-01-18 18:56:56', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(6, 9, 'Evaluation of our MBBS curriculum on Biochemistry', '<p>Evaluation of our MBBS curriculum on Biochemistry<br></p>', '2018-01-23 12:40:56', 'upload/attachment/147d60fe3b87d443c25161ddeaa640d1.docx', '<p class="MsoNormal"><b>Positive:<o></o></b></p><p class="MsoNormal">Timely submitted<o></o></p><p class="MsoNormal">Properly submitted<o></o></p><p class="MsoNormal">Most of the components of a curriculum is touched.</p><p class="MsoNormal"><o></o></p><p class="MsoNormal">Volume: Expected in 800 words. Written 815 words<b><br></b></p><p class="MsoNormal"><b>Challenges:</b></p><p class="MsoNormal">The expected changes in the participants are one of the way\r\nto chalk out the content of curriculum.<o></o></p><p class="MsoNormal">An introduction and a conclusion could be added to the text you have written.</p><p class="MsoNormal">in the introduction your basic understanding about the curriculum could be summarized.</p><p class="MsoNormal"><o></o></p><p class="MsoNormal">Evaluation of the curriculum should be done by students as\r\nwell.<o></o></p><p class="MsoNormal">More teaching staff / more teachers skilled in teaching\r\nmethodology are needed.<o></o></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class="MsoNormal">There are many constrains at the institution level, teachers\r\ncommitment , facilities available , students motivation in implementing the\r\ncurriculum in the institution.<o></o></p>', NULL, '2018-01-23 18:40:56', 'F'),
(7, 18, 'Development in ongoing curriculum for Psychiatry in MBBS level in Bangladesh. ', '<div xss=removed>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" xss=removed><span xss=removed>Asia has about\r\n25% of the world''s population. One-fifth of the mentally ill in the world live\r\nin this region but mental-health manpower is grossly inadequate</span><span xss=removed>. Most of the patient’s first contact is the\r\nprimary care physician for treatment. Unfortunately due to a deficient training\r\nat the undergraduate level, most doctors are unable to recognize and correctly\r\ntreat psychiatric disorders. The basic purpose of teaching and training at the\r\nundergraduate level is to prepare medical graduates to serve better at primary\r\nhealth-care level. The patients with physical illness have concomitant\r\nemotional problems requiring professional handling; therefore, teaching of\r\nPsychiatry at the undergraduate level becomes even more relevant and essential</span><span xss=removed>. </span><span xss=removed>Emphasis on teaching & training in\r\nPsychiatry in undergraduate curriculum is low. In many of the colleges the\r\ndepartment of Psychiatry has come into existence recently, and the faculty\r\nteaching the undergraduates is relatively junior and not fully experienced in\r\nteaching undergraduate.</span><u><span xss=removed><o></o></span></u></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" xss=removed><span xss=removed>Bangladesh Medical & Dental Council (BMDC) is following the\r\ncurriculum at present that have been formed in the year 2012. If we discuss\r\nBMDC curriculum including the points stated in Davidoff 1996 model, it’s a good\r\none stating the objectives. One of the objects should be having clear knowledge\r\nabout medico legal problems regarding psychiatry and dealing effectively with\r\nchallenging patient’s weather mentally ill or not. Medico legal aspect of\r\npsychiatry should be included in content as mental health act is on the\r\nprocesses of publishing in Bangladesh. However this ongoing curriculum is a\r\ngood one regarding integrity of clinical and preclinical subject. Medical\r\nstudents are now having clinical subject classes from 2<sup>nd</sup> phase that\r\nis after first one and a half year. They get placement in clinical class of\r\nPsychiatry department for 3 weeks in 3<sup>rd</sup> phase. Another 1 or 2 weeks\r\nshould be added in 2<sup>nd</sup> and 4<sup>th</sup> phase which will increase\r\ntheir interest and skills to deal with mentally ill patients as well as\r\nchallenging patients or relatives or friends of the patients in some emergency\r\nsituations. Options can be Field trip or Tertiary care hospital/ De addiction clinic\r\nvisit in the 2<sup>nd</sup> phase instead of ward placement. We can add some\r\nshort scales to measure anxiety, depression and MMSE as teaching aids. Time\r\nallocated for lecture is 20 hours. Instead of lecture, or reducing the time of\r\nlectures we can adopt more Student centered, Problem based, integrated method\r\nwhich will include all the points of SPICES model and Spiral curriculum. After\r\na short discussion with my students and from my personal experience I have\r\nfound that learning by doing is the best option. We can assign 10 cases of\r\nmental illness per student from phase 2 onward for taking care as a whole and\r\nmaintaining liaisons with other departments as needed. There will be small\r\nexams in every 6 months and during the final exam they will present the cases\r\nas a follow up study. One supervisor Psychiatrist will be guide all through and\r\nthus they can learn by themselves and with interest. In assessment part my\r\nsuggestion is that one Psychiatrist must be present in a board of final exam. A\r\nformer Scottish Secretary, Ian Lang has wisely stated that “ I believe that\r\nteaching without testing is like cooking without testing”. Learning outcomes\r\ncan be measured by attitude of students towards psychiatry just after admission\r\nto medical college and after final exam. Many studies have shown that proper\r\nexposure to Psychiatry changes the attitude of student towards positive.</span><span xss=removed> </span><span xss=removed>Tharyan <i>et al.,</i> in their study, observed that exposure\r\nto psychiatry training did have an influence on the change in attitude to\r\nmental illness, though it did not influence the choice of career. Rao <i>et\r\nal.</i> did a prospective study to elicit and monitor over time the medical\r\nstudents'' attitudes to psychiatry, psychiatrists, psychiatric patients and\r\ntheir treatment. There was a significant shift in favorable direction in the\r\ngeneral attitude to psychiatry, both before and after training. Majority of\r\nthem considered psychiatric specialty as challenging and scientific, and almost\r\nall felt that too little time is being spent on psychiatry in UG curriculum.\r\nHowever regarding educational environment, Psychiatry departments in all\r\nmedical colleges should be strengthened with a minimum strength of 20 beds and\r\na minimum faculty consisting of one professor, one associate professor and two\r\nasst. professors/lecturers.<o></o></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" xss=removed><span xss=removed>Psychiatry curriculum has obvious gap in the declared and taught part\r\nthat can be rectified only if policy and decision makers recognize the\r\nimportance of Psychiatry, not only in medical education but also in primary\r\nhealth care. The basic problem is that students can feel and empathize for the\r\nphysically ill, but they are overwhelmed by fear when they see the mentally ill.\r\nThe objective of undergraduate psychiatric education should be to equip medical\r\nstudents with core psychiatric knowledge useful in daily medical practice\r\nrather than filling curriculum time. Students are overloaded with brain\r\nchemistry, neurotransmitters research data on psychoses but are starved of\r\nrecognition of anxiety states, depression in non-psychiatric medical settings. Primary-care\r\npsychiatric problems, anxiety, depression are in abundance in primary-care\r\nclinics and medical wards where Psychiatry is to be taught in MBBS level. The\r\nundergraduates may be taught the psychiatric manifestations of common physical\r\ndisorders like delirium, which is found in abundance in medical and surgical\r\nwards. In most of the medical colleges of this region, knowledge of psychiatric\r\nillnesses is not evaluated in the examinations, psychiatric cases are not kept\r\nin clinical examination and viva voce part also seldom covers Psychiatry. Long-term\r\nplans should focus on reforming undergraduate medical education to incorporate\r\nexpanded, structured training in Psychiatry so that M.B.B.S. doctors are well\r\nprepared for the high standards of postgraduate training and examinations. The\r\nfuture doctor should be sympathetic towards patients with psychological\r\ncomplaints, be able to detect mental disorders and treat simple cases and be\r\naware when to seek a specialist''s help. <o></o></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" xss=removed><span xss=removed><o> </o></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" xss=removed><span xss=removed>References-<o></o></span></p>\r\n\r\n</div><div xss=removed>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>1.<span xss=removed>    </span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Trivedi JK, Goel D, Kallivaylil RA, Isaac M,\r\nShrestha DM, Gambheera HC. Regional cooperation in South Asia in the field of\r\nmental health. World Psychiatry. 2007;6:57–9.</span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" xss=removed><span xss=removed>2. Trivedi JK, Dhyani M.\r\nUndergraduate psychiatric education in South Asian countries. Indian J\r\nPsychiatry. 2007 Jul-Sep; 49(3): 163–165.</span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" xss=removed><span xss=removed>3. </span><span xss=removed>Manickam LSS Rao TSS.\r\nUndergraduate medical education: Psychological perspectives from India. Indian\r\nJ Psychiatry. 2007 Jul-Sep; 49(3): 175–178.</span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" xss=removed><span xss=removed>4. John A Dent, Ronald M Harden. A practical guide\r\nfor medical teachers; 2005. Second edition.</span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" xss=removed><span xss=removed>5. </span><span xss=removed>Tahmina Begum. Concepts of medical education ; 2013. First edition.<o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpLast" xss=removed><span xss=removed>6.<span xss=removed>    </span></span><span xss=removed> </span><span xss=removed><a href="http://bmdc.org.bd/mbbs-curriculum-update-2012/">http://bmdc.org.bd/mbbs-curriculum-update-2012/</a></span></p></div>', '2018-01-18 12:10:27', 'upload/attachment/7093b0d79c9e64b94fdaad3f6a966cee.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL);
