(52, 42, 'Assignment on Educational objectives and competencies ', '', '2018-01-26 05:35:09', 'upload/attachment/49d7aa18041cad00ee34ffc50a2695c1.doc', '<p>Thanks for submitting your assignment. You have nicely mentioned details of importance of taxonomy. that,s good.</p><p>I have some some observation regarding educational objectives.</p><p>1. In cognitive domain---should include some prerequisite knowledge on delivery as well.</p><p>2. Psychomotor domain--- skill itself should not be a domain, omit the term basic from basic movement</p><p>3. Rewrite affective domain--- it should include patient related points such as counselling, motivation, if patient get hurt what to do etc.</p><p><br></p><p>Thanks again, go ahead.</p>', NULL, '2018-01-26 11:35:09', 'F'),
(53, 45, 'Importance of Educational objective and Taxonomy ', '', '2018-01-26 04:58:54', 'upload/attachment/6663b252791296fd6c4932168685b9ad.docx', '<p>Thanks for submitting your assignment.</p><p>I have some observation.</p><p>1. When you mentioned- learning objectives--- starts with describe the physiology-Please write action verve which is more specific, and instead of physiology write more specific term of that particular topic.</p><p>2. Again explain is not a good action verb-- try to be more specific and measurable</p><p>3. Tnstead of the word treat--- change like way of management/ points of treating the patient/ as you think</p><p>4. Demonstrate is a good action verb.</p><p>5. Include at least one objectives on affective domain.</p>', NULL, '2018-01-26 10:58:54', 'F'),
(54, 48, 'Describe importance of taxonomy & learning objective in educational program. Write at least 5 specific objectives on any topic of your speciality according to the hierarchies in each learning domain', 'Assignment\r\nA helpful way to approach any challenge is to use a taxonomy as a guideline. A taxonomy is just a fancy term for the practice and science of classification. Taxonomies are developed to provide a framework for organizing a continuum along an underlying structure. \r\nTaxonomies of learning are the hierarchical classification in the field of education, have been developed by various groups concern with educational problems to help teachers to formulate precisely the educational objective. \r\nThe important taxonomies are Bloom''s Taxonomy, SOLO Taxonomy (Structure of Observed Learning Outcome) and McGuire preparation for achievement test. Educational psychologist consider three working levels of taxonomy to satisfy the need of evaluation\r\nIn 1956, Dr. Benjamin Bloom and several other educational psychologists published set of guidelines for developing educational objectives. Known as Bloom’s Taxonomy, this framework clarified the different stages of learning into three main domains: cognitive, psychomotor and affective.\r\nBloom’s taxonomy primarily provides instructors with a focus for developing their course learning objectives. It can be used to increase one''s understanding of the educational process. \r\nBloom''s taxonomy was developed to provide a common language for teachers to discuss and exchange learning and assessment methods. \r\n      Importance of taxonomy in educational program:\r\n1)  Taxonomy is a helpful tool in writing objectives and identifying how well the students comprehend a concept. \r\n2) It indicates the type of learning outcome that should be considered and it also provides a framework for classifying those outcomes.\r\n3) Specific learning objectives can be derived from the taxonomy, though it is most commonly used to assess learning on a variety of cognitive levels.\r\n4) It helps to determine the sequence of a segment of course to formulate instructional design and evaluation system.\r\n5) It also help educators focus on all three domains when teaching, thus creating a much more holistic form of education that can fit different learning styles and increase retention.\r\n6) It encourages higher-order thought in the students by building up from lower-level cognitive skills.\r\n7)  It also helps in Knowing the different levels and looking for where students fall among them  that will enable the fascilitators to move them from a basic level of understanding to a more complex level. \r\n8) This understanding facilitates the prioritizing of material and can steer the organization of lessons to maximize class time. For example, lower-level skills (e.g., memorizing factual knowledge) can be developed before higher-level skills are introduced (e.g., analysis of relationships).\r\n9) Beyond writing objectives, taxonomy is also extremely helpful in assessing students’ understanding of concepts.\r\n10) Taxonomy can be used as a checklist to ensure that all levels of a domain have been assessed and align assessment methods with the appropriate lessons and methodologies.\r\n11) It provides common grounds and makes comparison of various teaching programs.\r\nThe taxonomy guides all about in an educational program.\r\nIn this way, the taxonomy also makes it easier for instructors to maintain consistency between assessment methods, content and instructional materials and identify weak areas.\r\nLearning objectives are also called instructional objectives or performance objectives. They are the statements that describe what students will be able to do once they successfully complete a unit of instruction .\r\n Learning objectives are goals, not the activities performed to achieve those goals.\r\nA good learning objective is specific, measurable, and clearly stated. Learning objectives are a critical component of instruction. It describes the learner behavior It describes the behavior that can be seen or heard. Good learning objectives are consistent with the goals of the course and curriculum.\r\n     Importance of learning objective educational program :\r\n1. It provides a guideline for content\r\n2. Helps in preparing a lesson plan\r\n3. Provide course developers guidance on selecting suitable: \r\no instructional materials;\r\no teaching methods, including learning activities and use of technology;\r\no assessment methods.\r\n4. Help students focus on what they are expected to learn, and understand how they will be assessed.\r\n5. It provides a guideline of evaluation\r\n6. A clearly stated learning objective can help an instructor create appropriate learning activities to help students acquire the desired skills and select good assessment tools to evaluate students'' achievement.\r\nThat’s why it is always emphasized that learning objectives should be specific, measurable, attainable, relevant, transferable. Learning objectives target knowledge, skills or attitudes for change. Good learning objectives are consistent with the goals of the course and curriculum\r\n\r\nI am from Biochemistry specialty and my topic is “Clinical Biochemistry and Endocrinology”\r\nFrom cognitive domain:\r\nAt the end of the course, the student will be able to:\r\n• Define bilirubin and state different types of serum bilirubin\r\n• Explain the mechanism of development of hyperbilirubinaemia\r\n• State the indication of measurement of serum bilirubin\r\n• Differentiate different types of jaundice from serum bilirubin level\r\n• State the other biomarkers to differentiate different types of jaundice\r\nFrom psychomotor domain:\r\nAt the end of the course, the student will be able to:\r\n• Asses the subject whether he is ready for the procedure (estimation of serum bilirubin)\r\n• Collect specimen properly from the appropriate site without any complication\r\n• Perform the test properly by using appropriate reagent and instruments\r\n• Interpret the test results\r\nFrom Affective domain:\r\nAt the end of the course, the student will be able to:\r\n• Attend the subject properly and listen his complains\r\n• State the subject about the importance of the test regarding his condition\r\n• Correlate the test result with the pathological condition\r\n• support the subject mentally\r\nEducational objectives are short, well structured statements that specifies what the learners are expected to achieve at the end of an educational program.\r\n\r\n\r\n', '2018-01-28 05:24:44', 'upload/attachment/125dd0434d1b2c69a31b47a7a7e83a94.doc', '<p class="MsoNormal" xss="removed" xss=removed><span xss="removed">Dear fellow<o></o></span></p><p xss="removed" xss=removed><span xss="removed">Thanks for your much effort for preparing  assignment. My observation are as below .<o></o></span></p><ul xss="removed" xss=removed><li xss="removed"><font color="#333333" face="Arial, sans-serif"><span xss="removed">Firstly write the </span><span xss="removed">assignment</span><span xss="removed"> no and your name & ID no;  </span></font>Introduction of the topic of assignment should be short description.</li><ul><li xss="removed"><span xss="removed">Specific objectives should have at least two things- <b>Task</b>(which include <u>act/action verb</u>, <u>Content</u> & <u>Condition</u>)  and <b>criteria</b>.</span></li><ul><li xss="removed"><span xss="removed">Your prepared specific objective are lacking criteria and conditions.</span></li><li xss="removed"><span xss="removed">The verb ''asses/interpret'' etc not indicate psycho-motor domain;<o></o></span></li></ul></ul><li xss="removed"><span xss="removed">Please rewrite accordingly and submit today. <o></o></span></li></ul><p xss="removed" xss=removed></p><ul xss="removed" xss=removed><li xss="removed"><span xss="removed">Prof Md Shah Alam (MBBS,DTCD, MCPS, MMEd)</span></li><li xss="removed"><span xss="removed">Prof & Head, Forensic Medicine</span></li><li xss="removed"><span xss="removed">Ibrahim Medical College</span></li></ul>', NULL, '2018-01-28 11:24:44', 'F'),
(55, 36, 'Importance of taxonomy and learning objective in educational program and example of specific objectives on a topic of nephrology according to the hierarchies in each learning domain', 'Assignment 2\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCertificate in Medical Education (CMEd)\r\nBIRDEM Academy\r\nModule: Contemporary issues in medical education\r\nUnit name: Educational objectives and competencies\r\nCode: Cl 2\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSubmitted by-\r\n\r\nMuhammad Abdur Rahim\r\nEmail: muradrahim23@yahoo.com\r\n Cell: +8801674534500, +8801741009000 \r\n\r\n\r\nFaculty information-\r\n\r\n\r\nProf. Abid Hossain Mollah\r\nEmail: professorahm@yahoo.com\r\nCell: +8801711530323\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nTitle: Importance of taxonomy and learning objective in educational program and example of specific objectives on a topic of nephrology according to the hierarchies in each learning domain\r\nObjectives:\r\n1. To highlight the importance of taxonomy and learning objectives in educational program\r\n2. Example of a topic in nephrology with objectives indicating hierarchies of each learning domain\r\n\r\n\r\nIntroduction:\r\nEducation is a process that brings about expected changes in human behavior. Educational objective is defined as what the students should be able to do at the end of a learning period that they could not do beforehand. Mager defined educational objective as “an intent communicated by a statement describing a proposed change in a learner when he has successfully completed a learning experience”. Objectives may be general and specific. Learning objectives serve as guidelines for content, instruction and evaluation. There remains a SMART way of writing learning objectives. It should be specific, measurable, attainable, relevant and transferable. \r\nThe taxonomy of educational objectives is intended to provide for classification of the educational system. In 1956, Benjamin Bloom published taxonomy of learning objectives containing three major domains namely cognitive, psychomotor and affective domains. \r\nImportance of learning objectives:\r\nLearning objectives is the cornerstone in any educational program. These guide the whole process of teaching learning for the particular goal(s). If the general and specific objectives are not set from the beginning, it is impossible to plan the curriculum, its content, how these acts will be done and how will be assessed. So, without objectives no educational activity is set. It will be like that of sailing in the sea without the destination and a compass.\r\nAim is the overall direction like aim of undergraduate medical education (MBBS) is to make medical graduates able to serve community needs. The general objective of this program is to ensure some defined knowledge, skills and attitudes that students should attain throughout the course. The specific objectives are further details; suppose, to deal a patient with pulmonary tuberculosis they should be able to state symptoms of pulmonary tuberculosis, elicit relevant clinical findings (if present), plan for investigating the case, make a treatment plan and counsel the patient and caregiver(s)/family members regarding importance of treatment adherence, possible adverse effects of drugs, transmission of disease (tuberculosis) etc.\r\nImportance of taxonomy:\r\nTaxonomy of educational objectives serves different objectives:\r\n- Indicates the type of learning outcomes that should be considered\r\n- Provides a framework for classifying those outcomes\r\n- Directs attention towards changes in students’ performance in a variety of areas\r\n- Forms the blue print for the assessment tool\r\n- Provides common grounds and makes comparison of various teaching programs easier\r\nEvaluation of urinary tract infection (UTI) is planned with hierarchies of each learning domains\r\nCognitive domain:\r\nObjectives: Undergraduate medical students are expected to know following facts regarding UTI.\r\nEvaluation Why a patient with UTI is not responding to oral ciprofloxacin? \r\nThink about antibiotic resistance\r\nSynthesis\r\n Accumulation of facts e.g. clinical presentation, examination findings and lab. reports to make a diagnosis of UTI\r\nAnalysis Analysis \r\nApplication Ability to plan diagnostic tests in suspected UTI cases\r\nComprehension Ability to make a diagnosis of UTI from a given scenario \r\nRecall Define UTI\r\n\r\n\r\nPsychomotor domain:\r\nObjectives: Students are expected to perform relevant clinical examination in a setting of UTI/pyelonephritis.\r\nOrganization  Student may show peers how to examine for renal angle tenderness\r\nAdaptation  Advanced learner may perform the act in a different situation like sitting position\r\nComplex overt response Students perform in presence of trainer\r\nMechanism  Trainer performs the act (identifies anatomical landmark first)\r\nGuided response  Trainer will describe first “how to examine for renal angle tenderness?”\r\nSet  Student stands on right side of examination couch\r\nPerception  Candidate is able to understand the instruction “examine for renal angle tenderness” in suspected UTI (pyelonephritis) \r\n\r\nAffective domain:\r\nObjectives: Students are expected to counsel patient/family member(s) regarding UTI.\r\nCharacterization by value Internalize in candidate’s behavior for further cases\r\nOrganization  Have to be ready to offer effective help/empathy\r\nValuing  Will be ready to accept patients ideas/concerns\r\nResponding  Student/candidate will have to be ready to receive and answer question/quarries \r\nReceiving  Instruction: This 35-year-old diabetic patient is having recurrent UTI. Counsel her regarding the disease and consequences\r\n(Can recognize the situation when patients and care givers are waiting for information received from lab. reports)\r\n\r\nConclusion:\r\nEducational objectives are the core of an educational program. In any given topic of medical education, efforts should be given to organize objectives in different domains whenever possible for a better learning outcome.\r\n', '2018-01-28 18:03:34', 'upload/attachment/609595b11e502d1c92d15743233404d1.doc', '<p>Well written!</p><p>While writing learning objectives, it is important to select appropriate action verb</p><p>You did not write anything on the task- writing 5 learning capabilities that human can learn<br></p>', NULL, '2018-01-29 00:03:34', 'F'),
(56, 50, 'Assignment: Taxonomy and Learning Objectives in Educational             Program. Specific objectives according to the hierarchies in different learning domain.', 'Taxonomy and learning objectives in educational program.\r\nLearning objectives:\r\nThe first step of educational program planning is deciding and conveying the learning objectives of the educational program in a systematic manner. Learning objective is a clearly written, specific statement of observable student behaviors that can be measured that can be contribute to the teaching and learning goals. \r\n\r\nImportance of learning objectives: \r\n1. To meet the need of the institutional objectives.\r\n2.To ensure learner centered education.\r\n3. To convey  a systematic delivery of content by the teaching stuff. \r\n4. To provide  specific aims and objectives that maintains harmony, determination  to achieve the goal and to determine appropriate instructional methods to achieve the target.\r\n5. To formulate clear and intended outcome base education and to specify in describing learning outcome.\r\n6. To establish  a guide for teaching method material, constructing tests and other instrument for evaluating students achievement in any educational program that is directly linked o assessment .\r\n6. To compel learner an educational course that is in clarity and understandability.\r\n7. To ensure study course that is feasible within the allocated time and resources available.\r\n 7. To benefit both teachers and learner by ensuring the specificity  about what knowledge, skills and attitudes are expected to be attained by the learners from the session.\r\n8. To facilitate the opportunities of observable qualities of learner e.g. written, spoken, performed as well as measurable qualities such as rating, grading and marking. \r\n9. To determine the direction  specifically to have less chance to waste time and embark on unproductive activities by the learner.\r\n10. To help learner remain focused and minimize wastage of effort.\r\n 11.To serve a useful, specific planning  and reference point for authentic, accurate assessment .\r\n11. To clear student, teacher an assessor about what must be perform to show the competence.\r\n 12.To improve the chances of  success of any educational program.\r\n13.To form the foundation for selecting appropriate content , learning activities and assessment measures.\r\n14. To assemble the educational program  sufficiently comprehensive and global.\r\n\r\n\r\nTaxonomy of  educational   objectives :\r\nEducational objectives are structured around several classification systems  based on knowledge , skill and attitude  and classified into cognitive domain, psychomotor domain and affective domain. Each domain is further subdivided into a hierarchical patterns known  as levels. Generally, leaning objectives at the lower levels are mastered first before higher level learning objectives are accomplished and the learners subsequently from one level to next as the learners need to attain certain factual knowledge about a topic before being able to understand the underlying concept and once they understand the concept well they are able to utilize or apply the concept into practice. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nImportance of learning taxonomy : \r\n1. To bring expected and objective change in learners behavior with respect to knowledge, skill and attitude that conceived as the changes in cognitive, psychomotor and affective domain of learning respectively.\r\n2. To indicates the type and  framework for learning outcome that should be considered.\r\n3. To direct attention towards changes in the student performance in a variety of areas.\r\n4. To generate the blueprint for forming the assessment tools in learners every domains and levels to ensure learners efficiency.\r\n5.To provide common grounds and makes comparison of various teaching programs. \r\n 6.To help educators and trainers to determine the appropriate instructional level for students.\r\n7.To determine the appropriate instructional methods to achieve the target.\r\n7. To specify the instructor about the level or depth to which extend  the learners should able to know the information.\r\n8.To establish without ambiguity and with specificity about the competency of learners that each learners should gain from the program.\r\n9.To mould the instructor  focused and also clarify about the different level of different domains. \r\n10.To serve as the baseline upon which the assessment will be based.\r\n \r\nSpecific objectives on Anatomy  according to hierarchies in each learning domains:\r\n\r\nTopic:  Focusing  and identifying  the slide under the  microscope on histology class. \r\n\r\nAt the end of the teaching session on this topic, students are expected to be able to perform the underlying tasks (levels) that are described under each domain:\r\n\r\nCognitive domain:\r\n\r\n 1. Enumerate the parts of the microscope and also proper staging of the slide under microscope.\r\n2. Interpret the mechanism of action of different parts of the microscope while focusing the slide.\r\n3. Perform properly by focusing the slide under the microscope.\r\n4. Distinguish and categorize the slide under the microscope. \r\n5. Summarize the total procedure of focusing  and identifying the slide.\r\n6.  Evaluate the factor that can cause of any error while focusing the slide under microscope.\r\n\r\nPsychomotor domain:\r\n1. Easily focus, identify  any slide by repeating an act according to the demonstration and also understand clearly the factor or activity  that causes any error while focusing the slide under microscope.\r\n2.  Modify the factor that can cause any error while focusing the slide .\r\n3.  Focusing the slide becomes habitual and perform tasks with some confidence and proficiency.\r\n4. Skilful, smooth, quick, accurate and automatic focusing of any slide.\r\n5. While focusing,  if there is any disturbance in the artificial light source of the microscope, the  learner will be  able to focus the slide under natural light source by adjusting the mirror (will be able to solve the problem by creativity or by new ideas ) . \r\n\r\nAffective domain:\r\n1. Noticing the anxiety of other students who could not able to focus the slide.\r\n2. Reassuring and helping those students while focusing the slide.\r\n3. Encouraging and influencing other students to focus and identify the different slides.\r\n4. Showing care to those students who have failed to focus the slide and help them to get over it.\r\n5. Take initiative to arrange extra classes and learn more about different slides. \r\n', '2018-01-26 18:48:41', 'upload/attachment/ea18dc1e26e55fb2f03a880c49c8140d.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
