is usually more important than tests and evaluations\r\n\r\nConclusion: Staff developers should be individuals who are well respected by their peers and have some educational expertise and experience in facilitating groups. “To teach is to learn twice “principle should be the main motivating factors for staff developer. To motivate faculty, we need to develop a culture that promote and encourage professional development, consider multiple approaches to achieving the same goal, tailor program to meet individual and organizational needs. Building a network of interested persons is integral to the faculty development program\r\n\r\nAssignment-3 \r\nCertificate in Medical Education (CMEd)\r\nBIRDEM Academy\r\n\r\n                  Module: Contemporary issues in medical education\r\n             Unit name: Educational environment and staff development\r\n\r\nTitle: write a plan to improve educational environment and how to improve staff development program of your own department.\r\nSubmitted by-\r\nShudhanshu kumar saha\r\nEmail- shudhanshukumarsaha@gmail.com\r\nCell 01759961995\r\n\r\n                                      Educational environment\r\n\r\nIntroduction:\r\nThe educational or learning environment can be defined in various ways. At its simplest it can mean the physical surroundings within which learning takes place, such as access to library facilities, seminar rooms or simulation equipment. However, references to the environment generally also encompass broader and less tangible notions of educational ‘climate’, ‘culture’ or ‘ethos’.\r\n In 2011 the Medical Education England (MEE) Medical Indicator Task and Finish Group went even further, writing that:  ‘An effective educational environment depends on the quality of the leadership, the quality of patient care, the nature of the infrastructure, and the preparation and support of trainers so that they are able to deliver their educational role.’\r\nThe American Medical Associatication (AMA) defined learning environment as ‘a social system that includes the learner (including the external relationships and other factors affecting the learner), the individuals with whom the learner interacts, the setting(s) and purpose(s) of the interaction, and the formal and informal rules/policies/norms governing the interaction.’ \r\nComponent:\r\nAMA goes on to describe it as comprising three broad components in any institution or setting: institutional culture, curriculum (both formal and informal) and good educational climate\r\nInstitutional culture: Individual faculty and institution used to decide what type of might be useful\r\nCourse and curriculum design: The designers of short and long courses should consider the relevance of the learning environment to the potential learners. The aims, objectives and assessment should be described. Teaching methods should build on learner’s experience.\r\nGood physical climate includes:\r\n• Adequate room size\r\n• Comfortable temperature\r\n• Avoid of distraction (noise, visual distraction inside or outside)\r\n• Seating arrangement should adequate\r\n• Audiovisual equipment should be available\r\nAll these factors of the environment that can affect concentration and motivation. Some are within teachers control, others not.\r\nMeasuring the educational environment:\r\nThe MEE Medical Indicators Task and Finish Group identified a range of indicators as the best measures for judging the quality of an educational environment. Survey tools, such as the Dundee Ready Education Environment Measure (DREEM), have been developed to enable ‘global readings and diagnostic analyses of undergraduate environments in medical schools and other health professions institutes’ \r\nDoes environment matter?\r\n If evidence of the effectiveness of a positive environment on learner outcomes is limited, the negative effects of an adverse climate seem to be well recognized. AMA, for example, refers to supervisors’ lack of professionalism during interactions with patients and trainees, pressure on learners to behave in ways they may perceive as unprofessional and the presence of harassment or bullying\r\nOn the other hand, the General medical council (GMC) 2011 State of Medical Education and Practice (SOMEP) report points to the effects of a positive environment. It notes research which ‘suggests that medical students and trainees gain from practical experience and positive role models’\r\nConclusion: So, improvement of these three environmental factors for the learning environment to the exclusion of other environmental considerations. Aside from population forecasts, community needs and relationship continue, for the most part to be ignored. The physical environment has been left to the architect and consulting engineers. Many building design solutions solved physical facility needs. Student representation on curriculum committees is one means of ensuring a more student centered course. Students who are having difficulties need to be identified early and given additional support\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n                                  Staff development program\r\n\r\nIntroduction:\r\n Staff development/faculty development becomes an increasingly important component of medical education. Staff development activities have been designed to improve teacher effectiveness at all levels of educational continuum (e.g. undergraduate, postgraduate and continuing medical education) and diverse programmes have been offered to healthcare professionals in many settings. Bland et al 1990 defined staff development is a planned programme designed to prepare institutions and faculty members for their various roles\r\nObjective:\r\n1. There should be clearly defined the goals and priorities\r\n2. Target audience\r\n3. Choice of program, content and methodology\r\n\r\n  Faculty development functions include\r\n• Teaching skill\r\n• Understand the institutional/ organizational culture\r\n• Determine appropriate goals and priorities\r\n• Mentoring program\r\n•   Conduct needs assessments to ensure relevant programming\r\n• Develop different programs to accommodate diverse needs\r\n• Incorporate principles of adult learning and instructional design\r\n• Offer a diversity of educational methods\r\n• Prepare staff developers\r\n• Evaluate and demonstrate effectiveness \r\nOthers are\r\n• Decentralized activities\r\n• Peer coaching\r\n• Self-directed learning\r\n• Computer aided instruction\r\nEffective faculty development program: Effective programs focus on the participants, teachers, the program instructors, instructional methods and characteristics of the participants teaching setting\r\nEffective faculty development programs have the following characteristics\r\n• Address the needs of the faculty participants and institution\r\n• Takes into account the work palace of the teachers\r\n• Integrate curriculum that emphasizes theory and practice\r\n• Opportunity for practice and feedback\r\n• Build relationship among faculty members\r\n• Train more them one person from a setting\r\n\r\nBrief discussion of few methods\r\n\r\nTeaching skill: Teaching skill is key content of staff development programme. The aim is to improve teacher’s skill in clinical teaching, small group facilitation, lecturing, feedback and evaluation. Staff development has an important role to play in promoting teaching as a scholarly activity and in creating an educational leadership, innovation and excellence. \r\nUnderstand the institutional/ organizational culture: Staff development programmes take place within the context of a specific institution or organization. It is imperative to understand the culture of that institution and to be responsive to its needs. Staff development programmes should capitalize on the organization’s strength and work with the leadership to ensure success\r\nIncorporate principles of adult learning and instructional design: Adult come to learning situations with a variety of motivations and expectations about teaching methods and goals. Key principles of adult learning include the following\r\n• Adult are independent\r\n• Adult come to learning situations with a variety of motivations and definite   expectations about particular learning goals and teaching methods\r\n• Adult demonstrate different learning styles\r\n• Much of the adult learning is relearning rather than new learning\r\n• Adult learning often involves changes in attitudes as well as skills\r\n• Most adult prefer to learn through experience\r\n• Incentives for adult learning usually come from within the individual\r\n• Feedback is usually more important than tests and evaluations\r\n\r\nConclusion: Staff developers should be individuals who are well respected by their peers and have some educational expertise and experience in facilitating groups. “To teach is to learn twice “principle should be the main motivating factors for staff developer. To motivate faculty, we need to develop a culture that promote and encourage professional development, consider multiple approaches to achieving the same goal, tailor program to meet individual and organizational needs. Building a network of interested persons is integral to the faculty development program\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', '2018-02-01 17:54:43', 'upload/attachment/0615792d466f532abf09379cf2158aec.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(95, 68, 'Write a plan to improve educational environment and how to improve staff development program of your own department.STAFF DEVELOPMENT', 'Assignment No: 3 \r\nModule: 1 Contemporary issues in medical education\r\nUnit: CI3 Educational environment and staff development\r\nFellow ID: 181020\r\nThe educational environment is an important determining factor of an effective curriculum as there is a strong association between teaching and learning. An enriched learning environment can lead to increased satisfaction, achievement and success as a practitioner. The educational environment has been defined as “environment experienced or perceived by the students as well as by the teachers”. \r\nThese perceptions would be based on three important aspects which include: the physical environment, emotional climate, and intellectual climate. As educational institutes continue to become more student oriented, students’ perceptions of higher educational facilities and services are becoming increasingly important. \r\nI can improve educational environment of my own department in following ways:\r\n1) By assessing and providing proper physical environment like – \r\n• the size of the room\r\n• Temperature of the room\r\n• Avoid distraction (noise, visual distraction)\r\n• Adequate sitting arrangement\r\n•  Adequate audiovisual equipments\r\n                                                                 \r\n2) By providing well equiped laboratory with adequate tools, instruments and reagents\r\n3) By maintaining number of teachers with required qualifications and teacher student ratio\r\n4) By maintaining good student teacher relationship\r\n5) By providing with appealing salaries;and a safe, secure, and comfortable facility to high caliber educators; and by  providing even basic needs for students, such as adequate nutrition, health care, adequate rest, and support at dormitory for homework \r\n6) By planning an academic calender according to course curriculum \r\n7) By discussing with the faculty members about the teaching learning methods to make the curriculum easy by encouraging small group teaching, PBL, \r\n8) By arranging Departmental seminar with the involvement of students and teachers\r\n9) Providing assignment to the students under the guidance of teachers \r\n10) By ensuring good source of informations by developing enriched libraries along with computer and internet facilities\r\n11) By developing virtual learning environment (or VLE) which is increasingly common in higher education and also in medical education. VLE can provide course information such as study guides, forms, workbooks, time tables of exam, academic calendars of schedule events both for students and staffs. Blending of traditional learning and VLE can improve the educational environment.\r\n12) By developing teaching and technical staff of the department\r\n13) As learning environment affects student’s motivation and achievement, it is important to get feedback from the students on how they feel about their learning environment. Students’ perception of the educational environment is a useful basis for modifying and improving its quality. \r\n14) By assessing teacher’s perception about the educational environment is also very important for improvement\r\nTo measure medical and health education environment, the Dundee Ready Education, Environment Measure (DREEM) was developed. \r\n\r\nStaff development or faculty development has become an increasingly essential component in medical education. \r\nStaff development can be viewed as the activities and programs that help staff members learn about their responsibilities, develop required skills and competencies necessary to accomplish institutional and national goals and purposes and grow personally and professionally to prepare themselves for the advancement in the institution or beyond the campus.\r\nStaff development  program take place within the context of a specific institution  and department. It is important to clearly define goals and priorities of the department and according to this we can develop our staffs. \r\nI can improve staff development program of my own department in following ways:\r\n1) Workshop: We can arrange workshops on specific topics like MCQs, SAQs or OSPEs 6 monthly for our teachers by the experts on medical education and  can also send them to other institute like CME for  workshop and can encourage them to share their new achievements.\r\n2)  Short courses: we should always up to date about the short courses that are beneficiary to our teaching staffs according to their educational qualifications and should inform them and encourage them about the courses.\r\n3) Seminars: We can allow our teaching staffs to organize seminars on a specific topic at the the end of each month in the presence of Head of the Department and other seniors and experts who can give them positive feedback.\r\n4) Consultation with professional educators: With the help of an expert of medical education we can guide our teaching staff to make their lesson plan accurately\r\n5) Integrated longitudinal programes: By this program, faculty members allocate 10- 20% of their working hours for improving their educational knowledge and skills by maintaining other activities\r\n6) Peer coaching: It is also called co-teaching. It enables individualized learning and foster collaboration. It also allows health care professionals to learn about each others as they teach togather\r\n7) Mentorship: It is a valuable but underutilized staff development strategy. It promotes the socialization, development and maturation of academic faculty.\r\n8) Self directed learning: It promotes reflection -in -action and reflection- on- action. Teachers should be encouraged to determine their own needs through self reflection, evaluation by students, peer feedback and they should learn to design their own developmental activities. \r\n9) Computer aided instruction: This is closely tied to self-directed learning initiatives. Web based learning can allow for individualized programs targeted to specific needs and the sharing of resources.\r\n10) Performance reward: Staffs can be rewarded for their performances which can motivate them for self development\r\n11) Staff developers should be well trained, experienced and creative.\r\nAs job descriptions, individual goals and even the mission of institution or department may change so staff development plans will be reviewed on a regular basis. Changes to staff development plan shall be made as needed. Both the supervisor and the staff members must agree upon changes.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', '2018-02-06 05:12:30', 'upload/attachment/4ddcaba71e8043e2af7fc8493d6d24a1.doc', '<p>Tanks for your effort. In the strategies for improvement of educational environment, it would be better if  you write the strategies under the heading of physical setting, institutional culture and context  and operation characteristic. In improvement of staff development strategies  Institutional and departmental strategies, faculty strategies  should also need to be mentioned. you only write the methods of development. </p><p>However our assignment is accepted.</p><p>Prof shah Alam</p>', NULL, '2018-02-06 11:12:30', 'F'),
(96, 69, 'Write a plan to improve educational environment & how to improve staff development program of your own department.', 'Dr. Md. Towhidur Rahman         ID- GD2GOB\r\nName of the assignment – Write a plan to improve educational environment & how to improve staff development program of your own department.\r\nPlan to improve educational environment in my department (Radiology & Imaging) :\r\nLearning environment is an educational approach, cultural context, or physical setting in which teaching & learning occur. An improved learning environment is very important for achieving a successful educational outcome. We take a policy to develop our own strategy so that every faculty member can get a scope to develop their own carrier.\r\nOperational characteristics: \r\nThe operation of the educational facility can have a determining role of the nature of the learning environment. Before improvement of educational environment of the department operational characteristics of my department should be known which includes-\r\n• Organization type: Private.\r\n• Structure: Less structured\r\n• Schedule: Academic year (July session in every year), class periods (8am to 12 pm)\r\n• Staffing: Number of teachers – 10, other staff – 60.\r\n• Attendance: Student attendance.\r\n• Teacher certification: Post graduate degree-MD, M phil, FCPS\r\n• Assessment: Testing and standards provided by academy.\r\n• Partnerships and mentoring: Relationships between the learning environments and outside entities or individuals in general study.\r\n• Organizational model: Departmental.\r\n• Curriculum: The subjects comprising a course of study.\r\n\r\nA learning culture is a collection of organizational conventions, values, practices and processes. These conventions encourage employees and organizations develop knowledge and competence. Culture affects the behavior of educators, students, staff & community.\r\n\r\nTo create a learning culture into my department following key steps are as follows-\r\n• Formalize training and development plans- For a learning culture to be ingrained, it should be mandatory for all individuals in the department. Example – Hazards of radiation.\r\n• Give recognition to learning-  Employees who have successfully learned new skills and abilities should be recognized and encourage others to follow suit.\r\n• Get feedback-  Sessions and polls should regularly be done to evaluate the benefits of training and development, as well as to determine whether the training investment is well spent.\r\n• Promote from within- One of the advantages of training is having employees who are ready for a bigger role. Announce an internal job posting to encourage employees to gain knowledge.\r\n• Develop knowledge and information sharing into a formal process- People will be more encouraged to share knowledge and information if they are required to do so. Formalizing the process makes sure that everyone who needs the information gets it.\r\n\r\nLearning styles may be included – \r\n*Active learning - Active learning is a model of instruction that focuses the responsibility of learning on learners, not on teacher-led instruction, a model also termed student-centered. It is based on the premise that in order to learn, students must do more than just listen: they must read, write, discuss, or be engaged in solving problems.\r\n*Passive learning- Passive learning, a key feature of direct instruction, has at its core the dissemination of nearly all information and knowledge from a single source, the teacher with a textbook providing lessons in lecture-style format.\r\n* Hands on learning – Active & experiential learning, predates language & the ability to convey knowledge by means other than demonstration.\r\n* Differentiated learning - Direct instruction is expanding to include students conducting independent or guided research with multiple sources of information, greater in-class discussion, group collaboration, experiential (hands-on, project-based, etc).\r\n* Progressive education - Includes qualities such as learning by doing (hands-on projects, experiential learning, integrated curriculum, problem solving, critical thinking, group work, social skills development).\r\n* Constructivist education- It is a movement includes active learning, discovery learning, and knowledge building, and all versions promote a student''s free exploration within a given framework or structure. The teacher acts as a facilitator who encourages students to discover principles for themselves and to construct knowledge by working answering open-ended questions.\r\n* Traditional learning – To increase resources of libraries, proper space & ventilation and adequate seatings in teaching rooms, adequate instruments in lab etc.\r\n* e-learning – Providing learning & teaching resources such as searchable study guides & lecture materials, computed aided learning materials, discussion boards (both for general communication & for mediating online teaching & learning) & assessment. Large amounts of the users participation can be carried out online, being accessible –\r\n- From anywhere in the world.\r\n- At any time\r\n- At the convenience of the individual user. \r\n\r\nEffective learning environment can be achieved by – \r\n1. The students ask the questions.\r\n2. Questions are valued over answers.\r\n3. Ideas come from a divergent sources.\r\n4. A variety of learning models may be used – Inquiry based learning, project based learning, direct instruction, peer-to-peer learning, e-learning, mobile learning.\r\n5. Classroom learning empties into a connected community.\r\n6. Learning is personalized by a variety of criteria.\r\n7. Assessment is persistent, authentic, transparent & never punitive.\r\n8. Criteria for success is balanced & transparent.\r\n9. Learning habits are constantly modeled.\r\n10. There are constant opportunities for practice.\r\n\r\nHow to improve staff development program in my department (Radiology& Imaging)\r\nStaff development or faculty development has become an increasingly essential component in medical education. Staff development is a planned program designed to prepare institutions & faculty members for their various role. Now a days, virtual learning  gets a momentum to develop the environment of the institute.\r\nTarget population –\r\n1. Medical teachers\r\n2. Course coordinator / curriculum planners\r\n3. Administrator\r\n4. Organizer\r\n5. Healthcare professional\r\nApproaches-\r\nTeacher can take advantages of several types of format. Such as- \r\na. Workshops- One of the most popular formats because of their inherent flexibility & promotion of active learning.\r\nb. Seminars\r\nc. Short courses\r\nd. Consultation with professional educators\r\ne. By motivating  e-learning\r\nf. Traditional – Using libraries, study guides, lectures.\r\nFaculty members can use a variety of teaching methods within this format, including-\r\na. Interactive lectures\r\nb. Small group discussion & exercise.\r\nBased on changing needs & priorities, alternative formats are also be considered that include-\r\n1. Self directed learning\r\n2. Microteaching\r\n3. Peer coaching\r\n4. Mentoring\r\n5. Feedback from learners\r\n6. Videotape review\r\n7. Self evaluation\r\n8. Computer aided instruction.\r\n\r\n• Integrated longitudinal programme- In this programme, faculty members allocate 10-20% of their working hours for improving their educational knowledge & skills while maintaining the other activities.\r\n• Peer coaching – Key element of peer coaching includes the identification of individual learning  goals (improving specific teaching skills), focused observation of teaching by colleague & the provision of feedback, analysis & support.\r\n• Mentoring – A mentor is someone who has done helping someone who is just starting to do. Mentoring is almost always defined as a senior, more experienced person, guiding  a junior, less experienced one in preparing instructional method & lecture, delivering information.\r\n• e-learning –\r\n*Computer aided instruction – It is closely tied to self directed learning initiatives. This web based learning  allow for individualized programs targeted to specific needs & the sharing of resources.\r\n*Virtual learning environment (VLE) – is an integrated set of online tools, databases & managed resources that exist as a coherent system, functioning collectively in support of education. The goal is to provide students & staff with a range of online services & resources which will enhance the quality of student learning experience & improve the effectiveness & efficiency of teaching & learning. Providing learning & teaching resources such as searchable study guides & lecture materials, computed aided learning materials, discussion boards (both for general communication & for mediating online teaching & learning) & assessment. Large amounts of the users participation can be carried out online, being accessible –\r\n- From anywhere in the world.\r\n- At any time\r\n- At the convenience of the individual user. \r\n*Self directed learning – Teacher should be encouraged to determine their own needs through self reflection, evaluation by students & peer feedback.\r\n• Training of faculty in effective large group presentation- The variety of options for training faculty members in effective large group teaching includes courses & workshops, peer coaching, mentoring & consultations.\r\nDesigning a staff development programme- \r\n1. Understand the institutional culture.\r\n2. Determine appropriate goals & priorities.\r\n3. Conduct needs assessment to ensure relevant programing.\r\n4. Develop different programs  to accommodate diverse needs.\r\n5. Incorporate principles of adult learning & instructional design.\r\n', '2018-02-06 08:12:39', 'upload/attachment/84bed18a73e5daf56410be56f1dfe968.docx', '<p xss=removed><span xss=removed>Thanks\r\nfor preparing assignment.   some observation regarding your assignments are as bellow:<o></o></sp