(113, 74, 'e-learning and continuing professional development (CPD) ', '‘Online environment is merely an extension of face to face learning environment’, Discuss why? Describe the process of e-learning and its role in CPD.\r\n', '2018-02-09 23:13:05', 'upload/attachment/a77a0574163884544d0bff096e8a9dce.docx', '<p class="MsoNormal" xss=removed><b><span xss=removed>Online\r\nenvironment is merely an extension of face to face learning environment’, <o></o></span></b></p><p class="MsoNormal" xss=removed><b><span xss=removed>Introduction:<o></o></span></b></p><p class="MsoNormal" xss=removed><span xss=removed>Online\r\nenvironment is an educational approach, cultural context and physical setting where\r\nthe teaching & learning occur by using ICT (information & communication\r\ntechnologies). Many of the principles of face to face teaching & learning\r\nalso apply to online facilitation, such as <b>principles\r\nof facilitator’s</b> being the <u>guide</u> should allow student to work\r\nthemselves through issues instead of supplying information only; In addition\r\naddress the familiar issues of competition, conflict & responsibilities. E-learning\r\nenvironments are of two types: <b>Purely\r\nonline</b> or <b>Blended </b>(online and\r\nface-to-face). <o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<b><span xss=removed>1.<span xss=removed>       </span></span></b>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<b><span xss=removed>Discussion:<o></o></span></b></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>a.<span xss=removed>      \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Blended e-learning is an\r\nextension of face to face learning environment, here online environment and\r\nface-to-face both are used for the learning<o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>b.<span xss=removed>     \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Problem based learning (PBL): In\r\ne-learning the PBL may be practiced either as purely <b><u>e-PBL</u></b> or <b><u>Face to\r\nface e-PBL</u></b>. <o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" xss=removed><u><span xss=removed>Face to face e-PBL</span></u><span xss=removed>\r\nis an extension of face to face learning environment in online learning.<o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>c.<span xss=removed>      \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<b><span xss=removed>‘Synchronous\r\nformal question and answer in a chat room</span></b><span xss=removed>’ is one way of\r\ne-learning process where the student and faculty meet online as in lecture\r\ntheatre.- an extension of face to face learning environment.<o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>d.<span xss=removed>     \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<b><span xss=removed>‘Formal\r\nclasses in Bulletin board’ </span></b><span xss=removed>is one way of online learning\r\nwhere student may involve in discussion panel session like SGT- an extension of\r\nface to face learning environment.<o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>e.<span xss=removed>     \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Audio conferencing using<b> VoIP</b>(Voice over internet protocol) or\r\nTeleconferencing by using Skype, a learner can interact with the teacher, is an\r\nextension of face to face learning environment.<o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpLast" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>f.<span xss=removed>       \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<b><span xss=removed>Video\r\nconferencing</span></b><span xss=removed> and <b>Web\r\nconferencing</b>: Here the student and faculty can interact much as live\r\nlecture, or live SGT. Both are the examples of an extension of face to face\r\nlearning environment.<o></o></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" xss=removed><span xss=removed> </span></p><p class="MsoNormal" xss=removed><b><span xss=removed>process of  e-learning and its role in CPD</span></b><span xss=removed><o></o></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" xss=removed><span xss=removed>Process\r\nof e-learning are structuring the Schedules, Rules & Protocol of human\r\nactivity involve in e-learning. E-learning contents include teaching materials,\r\nreference materials, materials of practice domain & guides. Contents may be\r\ncreated & determined by teacher or student selected or community supported.<o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>1.<span xss=removed>       </span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Process\r\nfor content (two types): Digital materials (websites, books, study guide,\r\nlecture slide,) and course content (syllabi/ Curricula).<o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>a.<span xss=removed>      \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Online processing for e<b>-</b>learning activities include <b>participating in</b> <u>online discussion</u>,<b> </b><u>online chatting</u>,<b> </b><u>conferencing</u> (Tele-conferencing,\r\nAudio conferencing, video conferencing).l<o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>b.<span xss=removed>     \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Online searching: Accessing\r\ne-learning content (e-journal, e-books); e-portfolios; assessment; exercise to\r\nstimulate thinking.<o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>c.<span xss=removed>      \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Processing of offline activities:\r\nInteractive simulation, animation, DVD, Reusable learning material.<o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpLast" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>d.<span xss=removed>     \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Instant messaging by email, Informal\r\ncourse related discussions.<o></o></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" xss=removed><span xss=removed> </span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>2.<span xss=removed>       </span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Process\r\nfor supporting logistic & e-administration: <o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>a.<span xss=removed>      \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Tracking of content &\r\nparticipant, managing placement, timetable, exam result. <o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>b.<span xss=removed>     \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Registration, financing, human\r\nresources, building etc.<o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>c.<span xss=removed>      \r\n</span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Audit, quality assurance &\r\ncompliance, scrutiny.<o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>3.<span xss=removed>       </span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Process\r\nfor assessment: Use of ICT for authoring, delivery, marking, feedback, analysis.<o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpLast" xss=removed>&lt;!--[if !supportLists]--&gt;<span xss=removed>4.<span xss=removed>       </span></span>&lt;!--[endif]--&gt;<span xss=removed>Process\r\nfor community support: content creation(Wikipedia, blogging), file\r\nsharing(youtube), and discussion (face book)<o></o></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" xss=removed><b><span xss=removed><o> </o></span></b></p><p class="MsoNormal" xss=removed><b><u><span xss=removed>Role of e-learning in CPD</span></u></b><b><span xss=removed>:</span></b><span xss=removed>\r\n<o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpFirst" xss=removed><span xss=removed>Continuing professional development\r\n(CPD) is a combination of approaches and techniques of </span><span xss=removed>continuous improvement</span><span xss=removed> of own learning and growth</span><span xss=removed> to keep up-to-date with current\r\nprofessional requirements</span><span xss=removed>\r\nin response to the need</span><span xss=removed>\r\n</span><span xss=removed>to maintain expertise\r\n</span><span xss=removed>post qualification.\r\nCPD is not restricted to formal of the job training, seminars or workshops but\r\ninformal gaining of the knowledge and skill in continuous, structured,\r\nprofessionally focused activities. <o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" xss=removed><span xss=removed>Traditional way of face to face course,\r\nseminars, workshop, reading journals or text, are not always possible due to\r\nworkload, family commitment, travel distance, cost, lack of library service\r\netc. <o></o></span></p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpMiddle" xss=removed><span xss=removed> </span></p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class="MsoListParagraphCxSpLast" xss=removed><span xss=removed>Online\r\nenvironment for CPD is ideally suited to meet the crisis. E-learning is more convenience,\r\nrelevance, individualization and suitable for self-assessment & independent\r\nlearning.</span><span xss=removed> <b>e-learning</b> </span><span xss=removed>demonstrates versatility, flexibility\r\nthat encourage interaction to learn in own time, at own pace and in own\r\npreferred order for self growth by constantly updating skills to secure\r\nprofessionally competent and committed to his own development. The individual\r\ncan participate in content creation(Wikipedia, blogging), file sharing(Youtube,\r\nFlikr,Instagram) and discussion(facebook, instant messaging). The\r\nindividual  may involve in formal\r\nquestion answer session in chat room, audio conferencing on free voice over\r\ninternet services(VoIP, skype), video conferencing and web conferencing by\r\nusing laptop with webcam, microphones etc.<o></o></span></p>', NULL, '2018-02-10 05:13:05', 'F'),
(114, 83, 'Online learning environment and Continuing professional development', 'Online environment is merely an extension of face to face learning environment.  \r\nComputing and the internet are merely the latest instances of technology use in education, and their novelty still attracts a distinct label of ‘electronic learning’ or, more typically ‘e-learning’. In its broadest sense, e-learning is the use of the internet for education. E-learning, often referred to as online learning encompasses a pedagogical approach that typically aspires to be flexible, engaging and learner centered; one that encourages interaction, and collaboration and communication, often asynchronously.\r\n A classroom setting and an online learning environment can be compared; both can serve the purpose of learning in particular way. We have to attend class physically, but in online course module, notes, e-mail messages and postings to discussion area read without being physically present. Research, participate in discussions (reading, responding and post to discussion area or chat room), collaboration with other students, asking questions (e-mail and/or post question in discussion area), submit assignments (via e-mail or the discussion topic with or without attachments), complete quizzes and exams, network / socialize with classmates all these are possible not only in traditional class but also in e-learning environment. The exciting thing about the online environment is that you can still do many of the usual ‘classroom’ activities - and at a place that is convenient for you. \r\nAttending class in online learning environment is primarily an asynchronous environment – that is, we don''t have to log on to the computer at exactly the same time as our instructor or classmates in order to attend class. We will however, have specific deadlines to meet for the reading assignments and learning activities. \r\nCourse content is provided within the online course. We have the option of reading this information while online, or printing the information and reading it later. Additional information may also be provided in the form of links to other valuable web sites, articles or textbook. Just as in a face-to-face classroom setting, our comprehension of information will be assessed. Assessment may be accomplished through the use of discussion questions, self-tests, case studies, role plays, etc.\r\nIn a classroom setting, the instructor may often pose a question. In many cases, the question leads to a serious discussion and/or debate with other students. This occurs in the online classroom through the use of discussion topics in the discussion area. One of the best features of an online discussion is that we don''t have to be present at exactly the same time in order to communicate with other members of this course. The online discussion environment uses topics and threads to organize conversations. A linked series of comments is called a discussion thread and each topic can contain several threads. \r\nOnline learning gives us an opportunity to share our discoveries with others, and learn from them. There will be times when we may need to work in small groups. Each member of the group will research and read specific information and share this with the other group members. Discussion topics are one way to collaborate online. We can also use e-mail to collaborate. Online courses have their own email package built right in so that only the students enrolled in the course can send and receive an e-mail message. Role plays and case studies may be used in online courses in order to provide us with real-life problems. Often, the discussion forum will be used to enable us solve these problems individually and with other classmates. \r\nThe instructor usually knows when we are confused or frustrated simply by our body language. In the online environment, the instructor cannot see this type of body language. This means that we must communicate when we don''t understand! We can use the email within the course to send questions to our instructor or post our question in the discussion area for all to see. We can also ask other classmates questions just as we would in a classroom setting. Our classmates come with a wealth of knowledge from diverse backgrounds and areas of expertise. Use the discussion topic to post a question for all to see or send a private email to a specific individual. Either way, communication is key. \r\nIn a classroom setting, classmates typically meet before or after class for a cup of coffee and a bit of socializing. This can still occur in the online environment using e-mail, the discussion area or chat rooms. Everyone likes know a bit about the people they are studying with. One of our first activities may be to post a profile. Sharing personal profiles makes the class more enjoyable and enables us to feel more connected while learning at a distance. So all these discussion leads to the conclusion that “Online environment is merely an extension of face to face learning environment”  \r\n\r\n E-learning For Continuing Professional Development.\r\nProfessionals in hundreds of fields must meet continuing education requirements to stay current in their fields and to maintain their professional licenses or certifications.  E-Learning is a great fit for continuing education because busy working professionals can fit it into their schedules more easily than traditional classroom courses. \r\nDesigning effective eLearning for continuing education is not so different from designing effective eLearning for anyone else. We should focus on some points though. First, give the learners a heads up on the system and technical support before asking them to log in. Second, make sure their organizations can give them the time and resources they need to learn. Third, keep the interfaces as simple as possible so learners can focus on the content. Fourth, balance theoretical and practical materials. Fifth, include a traditional end-of-course test when possible. And finally, give them an opportunity to connect with other professionals.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n1. https://www.bcit.ca/files/distance/pdf/bcitonlinelearning.pdf \r\n2. https://elearningindustry.com/continuing-professional-development-elearning-6-best-practices\r\n3. John A Dent, Ronald M Harden. A practical guide for medical teachers; 2005. Second edition.\r\n4. Tahmina Begum. Concepts of medical education; 2013. First edition.\r\n5. AMEE Guide 32: Part-1 e-learning in medical education guide (learning, teaching & assessment), Medical teacher; 2008;30. P-455-473.\r\n6. AMEE Guide 32: Part-2 e-learning in medical education guide (Technology, management & design), Medical teacher; 2008;30. P-474-489.\r\n\r\n', '2018-02-08 11:26:39', 'upload/attachment/acaaca0fb134901112244c01d2e1fccf.docx', NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL),
